  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He whom he persecuted with a thirst for blood, was, apart from this, a great sufferer, bowed down and poor and נכאה לבב, of terrified, confounded heart. lxx κατανενυγμένον (Jerome, compunctum); but the stem-word is not נכא (נכה), root נך, but כּאה, Syriac bā'ā', cogn. כּהה, to cause to come near, to meet. The verb, and more especially in Niph., is proved to be Hebrew by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 11:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Such an one who without anything else is of a terrified heart, inasmuch as he has been made to feel the wrath of God most keenly, this man has persecuted with a deadly hatred. He had experienced kindness (חסד) in a high degree, but he blotted out of his memory that which he had experienced, not for an instant imagining that he too on his part had to exercise חסד. The Poel מותת instead of המית points to the agonizing death (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 53:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 28:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " מותי) to which he exposes God's anointed. The fate of the shedder of blood is not expressed after the manner of a wish in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 109:16-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but in the historical form, as being the result that followed of inward necessity from the matter of fact of the course which he had himself determined upon. The verb בּוא seq. acc. signifies to surprise, suddenly attack any one, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 41:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The three figures in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 109:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are climactic: he has clothed himself in cursing, he has drunk it in like water (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 15:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 34:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), it has penetrated even to the marrow of his bones, like the oily preparations which are rubbed in and penetrate to the bones.n In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 109:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the emphasis rests upon יעטּה and upon תּמיד. The summarizing ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 109:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is the close of a strophe. פּעלּה, an earned reward, here punishment incurred, is especially frequent in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 40:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", e.g., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 49:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 40:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; it also occurs once even in the Tra, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 19:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Those who answer the loving acts of the righteous with such malevolence in word and in deed commit a satanic sin for which there is no forgiveness. The curse is the fruit of their own choice and deed. Arnobius: Nota ex arbitrio evenisse ut nollet, propter haeresim, quae dicit Deum alios praedestinasse ad benedictionem, alios ad maledictionem. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
